on first glance it would seem that garden in English is the natural cognate to Garten in German, and while it is true that both words can be traced to the same root word *gardô which meant something like fence or enclosure 'garden' isn't actually the native English word descended from that root word! In fact the native English word underwent palatalization which turned the proto-germanic /ɣ/ into modern English /j/ and yields us hence modern English yard. (yield btw was likewise affected and is hence cognate with modern German 'Geld' or English Geld as in Danegeld or Weregild)
Anyway English gets its 'garden' in a rather more complex way! Through the Istvaeonic branch, whence we also get modern Dutch, we get via the Frankish *gardō that was passed into the French giving it modern jardin and through the Norman variety found its way back to England after the Norman conquest as garden.
Interestingly the -in Ending which became in English the same -en ending as is found in the modern German actually derive from completely different sources. In German's case it derives its word final -n via the oblique case which eventually came to applied in the nominative as well whereas the English -en seems to derive from a diminutive form that was applied once the word had entered the romance languages
